# Workflow Rules

## Backlog Intake Order
- The backlog root (`backlog/` itself, not a subfolder) is the human's raw intake
  queue: requests the human drops there directly, not yet turned into specs.
- The specifier must DRAIN the backlog root before looking at any queued items.
  Root items take precedence over items already in `backlog/paused/` and
  `backlog/active/`.
- Draining a root item means: read the raw item, resolve ambiguity with the human
  if needed, write a proper spec for it (prose `description:` + Gherkin
  `acceptance:`), place that spec into `backlog/paused/`, and remove the raw item
  from the root so it is not processed twice.
- Only once the backlog root is empty may the specifier turn to queued work.
- This governs the specifier's intake order only. The coordinator's separate
  promotion order (paused before root) is unchanged.

## Concurrent Work Orthogonality
- Applies to the coordinator when `active_backlog_max_depth` > 1, so more than one
  parcel can be in flight at once.
- Before promoting the next item into `backlog/active/`, compare its scope (the
  files, modules, and areas named in the ticket's `description:`/`Scope:`) against
  the scope of every item already active or in flight.
- Prefer a concurrently-active set that is ORTHOGONAL — items that touch different
  files/modules/areas. Do not run two items that edit the same file or a tightly
  coupled area at the same time; overlapping concurrent edits cause merge
  conflicts and rework.
- If the next item by priority would overlap something already in flight, skip
  past it to the next orthogonal candidate, keeping priority and bugs-first order
  among the orthogonal candidates. If no orthogonal candidate exists, leave the
  slot empty and let the overlapping in-flight item finish before promoting the
  overlapping one — never force two overlapping items to run concurrently.
- This is a "where possible" preference, not an absolute bar: a lone high-priority
  item with no orthogonal companion still runs alone, and nothing is starved — the
  moment its overlapping sibling merges, promote it next.
- Orthogonality never overrides the hard caps: stay at or below
  `active_backlog_max_depth`, and keep bugs-first ordering among equally-orthogonal
  candidates.

## Worktree Discipline
- At startup, discover and remember the branch or worktree assigned to your role.
- If your assigned worktree is `master`, work in the main project checkout on its current branch; do not expect or create a `.worktrees/<role>` directory for that role.
- Work only in your assigned branch or worktree.
- Do not inspect, diff, merge, or base work on another branch unless that branch is specifically named in a handoff or explicit user instruction.
- Do not run `./swarm` from an agent worktree to repair helper scripts. If handoff helper scripts are missing from PATH, stop and report the startup failure.

## Temporary Files
- Use `./tmp/` in your assigned worktree for temporary files; do not use `/tmp`.

## Failure Conditions
- If the expected git layout or assigned worktree is missing, stop and report instead of silently working in the wrong place.
